N ay, Asteria, why weep'st thou for Gyges, Whom, enriched with Bithynia's rich cargoes, The first sparkling zephyrs of spring Shall waft back to thee, constant as ever?

By the south wind on Oricus driven,

At the rise of the turbulent goat-star, Unsleeping‚ he weeps, through the night, The dull chill of his partnerless pillow.

But the agent of Chloe, his hostess‚ T ells the youth that in her he has kindled A flame no less ardent than thine, In a thousand ways craftily tempting ι»

Warns him how the false consort of Proetus Duped her credulous lord, bylfeigned charges, Into plotting Bellerophon's death, For too chastely regarding his hostem* ,

Tells how Peleus, Hippolyte† slighted, And was all but consigned to dark Hades ;

⁴* Proetus, believing the story of his wife Anteia, that Bellerophon had attempted to seduce her, but unwilling himself to slay his guest, sent him to his father-in-law Iobates, king in Lycia, with sealed letters, in which Iobates was requested to destroy the bearer.
